Before you start, make sure to disconnect your MicroView from your computers USB Port.
For this circuit you will need a motor, transistor, 330R resistor and a red breadboard wire.
Insert your MicroView and Programmer with Pin 1 in hole C9.
Select your motor and insert its red wire into hole D21 and black wire into hole D25 your breadboard.
Select your transistor and insert it into holes A16-A18 of your breadboard as shown.
Select your diode and insert it into holes C21 and C25 of your breadboard.  Ensure the white strip is oriented as shown.
Select your resistor and insert it into holes F17 and E17 of your breadboard.
Select your green wire and insert it into holes I14 and I17 of your breadboard.
Select a red wire and insert it into holes A21 and the 5V rail of your breadboard.

Select a red wire and insert it into holes I10 and 
the 5V rail of the breadboard.

Select a yellow wire and insert it into holes B18 and 
B25 of the breadboard.

Select a black wire and insert it into holes B16 and 
the Ground rail of the breadboard.
Connect your MicroView to your computers USB Port.
Swipe Left to go to the next page
Swipe Right to go back to the previous page
If you have a keyboard you can also use the arrow keys
